abstract: Mayor Bill de Blasio said the spending was an effort to combat an unequal system in which parks in poorer neighborhoods were disregarded.
snippet: Mayor Bill de Blasio said the spending was an effort to combat an unequal system in which parks in poorer neighborhoods were disregarded.
lead_paragraph: Mayor Bill de Blasio on Thursday announced that he would spend $150 million to upgrade five large New York parks — $30 million to one in each borough — in what he called an effort to combat an unequal system in which parks in wealthier parts of the city were well financed while those in poorer neighborhoods were neglected.

lead_paragraph: Donald J. Trump’s struggling candidacy has now become a direct threat to Republican control of Congress, significantly increasing the likelihood that Democrats will take control of the Senate and cut substantially into the House Republican majority next year.

abstract: Other New York officials rushed to the scene of the Queens shootings. Mr. de Blasio was not among them, raising up a familiar question: When does a situation warrant a mayor’s presence?

lead_paragraph: In the hours after an imam and his assistant were shot dead on a Queens street on Saturday, several elected officials rushed to the scene.

abstract: No state is more central to the Republican candidate’s uphill quest than Pennsylvania, which has voted Democratic in the last six presidential elections.
snippet: No state is more central to the Republican candidate’s uphill quest than Pennsylvania, which has voted Democratic in the last six presidential elections.
lead_paragraph: The lunch group in Monessen, Pa., is evenly divided between Donald J. Trump supporters and Trump opponents. But the dark mood across the whole room suggests why this working-class town might end up favoring him in November.

abstract: A lavish municipal property bearing a presidential candidate’s name yields little for the Bronx residents who live nearby.
snippet: A lavish municipal property bearing a presidential candidate’s name yields little for the Bronx residents who live nearby.
lead_paragraph: Last summer, when Donald J. Trump’s presidential bid still seemed like a protracted April Fool’s joke, a lavish municipal golf course bearing his name — Trump Golf Links at Ferry Point — had just opened in New York City. This was many unhinged remarks ago, back in the early-morning hours of all the rancor, when he was condemning Mexicans as rapists and drug dealers best kept out of the country he hoped to govern, or as others would come to view it, tyrannize. Do you remember when you thought it would all end there? Even then, before the Trump candidacy had attained the fervor it would eventually acquire, there was reason to speculate whether his political volatility would imperil his business interests, and what it would mean for the city’s partnership with him if it did.

abstract: With no serious challenger yet emerging to take on the mayor in next year’s election, a recent poll suggests there could be an opportunity for a party insider running as an independent.
snippet: With no serious challenger yet emerging to take on the mayor in next year’s election, a recent poll suggests there could be an opportunity for a party insider running as an independent.
lead_paragraph: Maybe it was Mayor Bill de Blasio’s rough week at the Democratic National Convention, when he was relegated to a daytime speaking slot and upstaged by his archrival, Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo, and his predecessor, Michael R. Bloomberg.

abstract: The heads, on display at Princeton University, are replicas of zodiac heads once at the Old Summer Palace and are a commentary on historical memory.
snippet: The heads, on display at Princeton University, are replicas of zodiac heads once at the Old Summer Palace and are a commentary on historical memory.
lead_paragraph: PRINCETON, N.J. — On summer days at Princeton University, children splash in a fountain next to an unlikely piece of art: 12 large bronze heads of animals sitting atop poles in a line.

abstract: It’s 90 days until the election. Twice a week on our new podcast, the campaign team at The Times will make sense of the final, delirious phase of the campaign.
snippet: It’s 90 days until the election. Twice a week on our new podcast, the campaign team at The Times will make sense of the final, delirious phase of the campaign.
lead_paragraph: It’s three months until Election Day. To guide you through this final, delirious phase of the presidential campaign, The New York Times is drawing on our all-star team of reporters, columnists, magazine writers and analysts to create a new podcast. It’s called The Run-Up.
